 @Thetruth99  Climate change is a cycle that happens about every 5,000 years, with or without humans. It is determined by the Earth's location in space, and its location to the sun; three parameters, the tilt, the angle, and the wobble. The orbit of the Earth around the sun is a key factor - sometimes it's further, sometimes it's closer. 

Although modern humans pump vast amounts CO2 in the atmosphere, the current climate change is not the warmest. It is three times less warm than it was in the Medieval Warm Period (around 900-1300 C.E.).

After the warming of climate change, comes a cooling period. Interestingly, the more CO2 there is in the atmosphere, the colder the cooling period will be (historically speaking).

