 @Amused  "Hmm, so CO2 history didn't start till 1950?"

No. What I said is that for the last 2.6 million years there hasn't been more than 300ppm carbon in Earth's atmosphere, until 1950 when it started skyrocketing to 400ppm. 

I'm not sure where you're getting your figures from: during the Karoo Ice Age 360-260 million years ago, there was less than 300ppm carbon in Earth's atmosphere. That's one of the contributing factors to that ice age. There was no ice age during the Jurassic or the Cretaceous. There was a slight decrease in average global temperature between 112-118 million years ago, caused by a drop in atmospheric carbon (itself likely tied to the opening of the Atlantic Ocean and changes in ocean circulation). During the Cretaceous, the average temperature at winter at the poles was 14C and 17C at summer, compared to 0C at summer and -40C at winter at the North Pole today.
